Let's sketch our triangle first. [asy]
pair A, B, C;
A = (0, 5.196);
B = (-13, 0);
C = (13, 0);
draw(A--B--C--cycle);
label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
[/asy] We can see that the shortest angle bisector will be from the vertex $A$ (we leave the proof to the reader). We will call that bisector $AD.$ [asy]
pair A, B, C, D;
A = (0, 5.196);
B = (-13, 0);
C = (13, 0);
D = (0, 0);
draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--D);
label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, S);
[/asy] Since $\angle BAD = \angle CAD$ by definition and $\angle ABC = \angle ACB$ since $\triangle ABC$ is isosceles, we can see that $\angle ADB = \angle ADC = 90^\circ.$ This is useful, since we know that $AC = 14$ and $DC = \frac{1}{2} \cdot BC = 13.$ Therefore, we use the Pythagorean theorem to find $AD^2 = AC^2 - CD^2 = 14^2 - 13^2 = 27.$ Therefore, our answer is $AD = \boxed{3\sqrt{3}}.$

